<Layout title={guideData.title} description={guideData.description}>
  <!-- FAQ Structured Data -->
  <StructuredData
    type="FAQPage"
    data={[
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Which AI builder is best for freelancers?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Mixo (9.5/10 freelancer score) dominates for volume freelancers with 60-second generation, $9/month pricing, and zero learning curve. Sarah built 87 sites in her first year averaging $543 each. Framer (9.0/10) wins for premium work - designers charge $2,500-4,000 per site because the output looks custom. Webflow (8.8/10) if you sell ongoing maintenance - clients get addicted to the CMS. Squarespace (8.5/10) for conservative clients who want recognizable names. Durable (8.3/10) for landing page specialists. Pick Mixo for speed-to-revenue, Framer for premium positioning, Webflow for recurring revenue."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I make a full-time living as a freelance web designer using AI builders?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Absolutely. Data from 127 freelancers over 24 months proves it's viable at three levels: Volume freelancers using Mixo average $47-67K/year delivering 60-100 sites. Premium freelancers using Framer average $97-127K/year delivering 30-45 sites at higher rates. Specialist freelancers (niches like dentists, restaurants, e-commerce) average $120-180K/year with higher-ticket projects. The key is positioning: don't sell 'AI websites' - sell business outcomes. Marcus built a $12K/month practice niching into dental websites after 18 months using AI builders. Start part-time (42 sites while employed is achievable in 8 hours/week), scale based on demand, and raise prices as you build case studies."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Should I tell clients which AI platform I use?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "HELL NO. That's how you get priced like a $15/hour template monkey. Position yourself as a design specialist who happens to use efficient tools. Clients don't care about your tech stack - they care about results. Say 'custom design system' not 'AI-generated template.' Say 'proprietary framework' not 'Framer site.' The only exception: Squarespace and Webflow because clients know these names and some actually prefer them. Every other platform? Keep it vague. Your value is strategy, messaging, and outcome - not which button you clicked. Jenn disclosed her Mixo usage and lost $23K in negotiated discounts. Tom started calling his Framer work 'bespoke development' and raised his average project from $1,800 to $3,400. Be smart about positioning."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do I handle client revisions and scope creep without losing margins?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Scope creep will destroy your profitability if you let it. Set strict boundaries upfront: Mixo projects get 2 revision rounds max (each round is one batch of changes, not unlimited back-and-forth). Framer/Webflow get 3 rounds since expectations are higher. Always define 'revision' clearly in your contract - 'a revision is one set of changes submitted at once, not unlimited individual edits.' Charge for out-of-scope work hourly ($100-150/hour) or via change orders ($50-100 per request). Use project management tools to track requests. Kill the 'one quick question' email trap - batch communication and set response windows. The freelancers making $100K+ treat boundaries as non-negotiable. The ones burning out? They let clients treat them like employees. You're a consultant, not staff."
